<DocsLayout title="Read-after-Write Consistency">
  <h1>Read-after-Write Consistency</h1>
  <p>EntDB uses event sourcing: writes go to the WAL first, then the applier processes them into SQLite. By default, reads are <strong>eventually consistent</strong>. For immediate consistency, use the <code>after_offset</code> mechanism.</p>

  <h2>The Problem</h2>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`# Without consistency guarantee:
result = await plan.commit()

# This might return None — applier hasn't processed the event yet
task = await db.get(Task, result.created_node_ids[0], "acme", "user:alice")
# task could be None!`}
    go={`// Without consistency guarantee:
result, err := plan.Commit(ctx)
if err != nil {
    return err
}

// This might return nil — applier hasn't processed the event yet.
task, err := entdb.Get[*shop.Task](ctx, scope, result.CreatedNodeIDs[0])
// task could be nil!`}
  />

  <h2>Solution 1: Wait During Commit</h2>
  <p>The simplest approach &mdash; block until the write is applied:</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`result = await plan.commit(wait_applied=True, timeout=5.0)
# Returns only after the applier has processed the event

# Now reads are guaranteed to see the data
task = await db.get(Task, result.created_node_ids[0], "acme", "user:alice")
# task is always found`}
    goNote="wait_applied is not yet exposed in the Go SDK. Use Solution 3 (explicit wait) below — it's the same primitive, just one extra line."
  />
  <p>Latency: typically &lt;50ms. The server uses event-driven notification (not polling).</p>

  <h2>Solution 2: Offset-Based Reads</h2>
  <p>More flexible &mdash; commit fast, wait only when you need to read:</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`result = await plan.commit()  # returns immediately after WAL append

# Do other work...

# When you need to read, pass the offset
task = await db.get(Task, result.created_node_ids[0], "acme", "user:alice",
                    after_offset=result.receipt.stream_position)
# Server waits for the offset to be applied, then reads`}
    goNote="after_offset is not yet exposed on Get/Query in the Go SDK. Use Solution 3 (explicit wait) below."
  />
  <p>This is useful when the write and read happen in different parts of your code.</p>

  <h2>Solution 3: Explicit Wait</h2>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`result = await plan.commit()

# Wait for the offset explicitly
await db.wait_for_offset("acme", result.receipt.stream_position, timeout=5.0)

# All subsequent reads are consistent
tasks = await db.query(Task, "acme", "user:alice")`}
    goNote="WaitForOffset is not yet implemented in the Go SDK (tracked for vNext). Until then, the Go client receives result.Receipt.StreamPosition but cannot block on it server-side; rely on natural latency (<50ms typical) or call back briefly until the read returns."
  />

  <h2>When to Use What</h2>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Use When</th><th>Latency</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>wait_applied=True</code></td><td>Simple CRUD, user-facing writes</td><td>+10-50ms</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>after_offset</code></td><td>Write in one place, read in another</td><td>+0ms (if already applied)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>wait_for_offset()</code></td><td>Batch writes, then consistent read</td><td>+10-50ms once</td></tr>
    <tr><td>No guarantee</td><td>Background jobs, analytics, search</td><td>+0ms</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>How It Works Internally</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><code>plan.commit()</code> appends event to WAL, receives <code>stream_position</code></li>
    <li>Applier processes events, updates <code>applied_offset</code> per tenant</li>
    <li>When a read with <code>after_offset</code> arrives, server checks: is <code>applied_offset &ge; requested_offset</code>?</li>
    <li>If yes: execute read immediately</li>
    <li>If no: wait on an <code>asyncio.Condition</code> (event-driven, not polling)</li>
    <li>Applier notifies condition when it catches up</li>
  </ol>
</DocsLayout>
